Model Comparison on Iris Dataset

This project compares multiple machine learning models on the Iris dataset using a 2-fold cross-validation approach. The dataset is loaded from a CSV file and split into feature variables (sepal and petal measurements) and target labels (flower species). Since some models require numerical input, class labels are encoded into integers.

The dataset is divided into two equal folds. Each model is trained on one fold and tested on the other, then the process is reversed. Predictions from both folds are combined to evaluate overall performance.

A wide range of models are tested, including:

Regression Models: Linear Regression, Polynomial Regression (degree 2 and 3)
Probabilistic Model: Naive Bayes
Instance-Based Model: k-Nearest Neighbors (kNN)
Linear Models: Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA), Linear SVM
Tree-Based Models: Decision Tree, Random Forest, Extra Trees
Neural Network: Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP)

For regression-based models, predictions are rounded and clipped to match valid class labels.

Metrics Reported
Accuracy
Confusion Matrix
Tech Stack
Python
NumPy
Pandas
scikit-learn
